                <h3 class="subheading">News Details</h3>
                <p>Brixton Motorcycles is gearing up for its much-anticipated launch in India on November 18, marking its entry into one of the world’s largest two-wheeler markets. The brand, which has gained a loyal following in Europe for its classic, British-inspired designs, plans to introduce models that blend vintage aesthetics with modern engineering, targeting India's mid-range motorcycle market.</p>
                <p>
                    While specific models for the launch are yet to be officially confirmed, Brixton’s international lineup includes popular models like the Brixton Cromwell and the Crossfire.
                    The company will launch four models in India, including the Crossfire 500X, Crossfire 500XC, Cromwell 1200, and Cromwell 1200X.
                </p>
                <div class="row m-b20">
                    <div class="col-lg-12 col-md-12 text-center">
                        <img src="~/images/latestnews/2024/nov/brixtonmotorcyclestodebutinindiaonnovember18keydetailsrevealed/2.webp" alt="Brixton Motorcycles India Launch 1" />
                    </div>
                </div>
                <p>These motorcycles are known for their iconic retro designs, advanced technology, and robust build, appealing to both seasoned riders and those new to the retro motorcycle trend. The company’s entry is expected to provide direct competition to brands like <a class="for-link" asp-controller="Home" asp-action="TWBrandDetails" asp-route-brandId="18">Royal Enfield</a>, <a class="for-link" asp-controller="Home" asp-action="TWBrandDetails" asp-route-brandId="17">Jawa</a>, and <a class="for-link" asp-controller="Home" asp-action="TWBrandDetails" asp-route-brandId="23">Yezdi</a> in India.</p>
                <p>Brixton’s models are likely to feature single-cylinder engines in the 500cc to 1200cc range, designed for comfortable urban commuting and highway cruising. Key features may include LED lighting, ABS braking, digital instrument clusters, and fuel injection. Expected to be competitively priced, Brixton aims to capture the attention of India’s motorcycle enthusiasts.</p>
                <h3 class="subheading">Price in India (Expected)</h3>
                <p>Starting at ₹2.5 lakh and up to ₹3.5 lakh for top models, depending on specifications and engine size.</p>
                <h3 class="subheading">Specifications (Expected for Brixton Cromwell and Crossfire models)</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <span class="font-weight-700">Engine Options:</span> 500cc – 1200cc, Single-cylinder, 4-stroke
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="font-weight-700">Power:</span> 46 BHP to 82 HP depending on model
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="font-weight-700">Transmission:</span> 5-speed / 6-speed
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <span class="font-weight-700">Fuel System:</span> Electronic Fuel Injection
